Print your own fully functioning LED Flashlight!
(Electronics and batteries not included)
See jtfdailycheck.blogspot.com for more details
Disclaimer: The way I wired mine up ended up causing a short that ruined the batteries and melted the insulation on the wire! I made a few changes to the connections and it works fine. Please make sure your connections are very well insulated.

All of the parts should be able to print without support. Mine has two perimeters and 20% infill.
The threading on the caps has some built in tolerance, so getting the parts to fit shouldn't be a problem - my printer isn't extremely accurate and they fit perfectly. I included the Solidworks files in case you would like to modify them.
Other Parts:
A small, approx. 7mm pushbutton
Up to 4 - 5mm LEDs (I used the 'High Brightness White LEDs' from Radioshack)
Some wire
A spring
A large nut
A 50mm diameter cut circle of acrylic (or something clear to protect the bulbs)
Hot Glue
2 AA batteries
Assembly:
1) Hot glue a wire in the main body of the light with about 2 inches of excess wire on either end. Make sure the wire is within the ribs.
2) Attach the button in the back cap and solder the wire onto one of the terminals.
3) Solder and hot glue the spring onto the back of the button. (I also soldered and hot glued a small nut on the other side of the spring for better contact with the battery terminal). See photo.
4) Hot glue and solder the LED's (in parallel) to the cone, making sure that one LED has its anode and cathode accessible for connections.
5) Solder the wire to one of the LED's terminals. You may want to mock this up with alligator clips to see which direction the batteries will have to point. Mine is set up with the negative terminal at the back with the switch, but it really shouldn't matter.
6) Hot glue the large nut to the back of the LED assembly (see photo) and pinch the other LED lead in between the hot glue and the nut, creating a contact for the battery. I used a small piece of metal here to expand the contact size and keep the glue from insulating the contact. You may need to get creative here...
7) Cut out a circular piece of acrylic about 50mm - 52mm in diameter. I used 3mm acrylic, but there is plenty of room in the cap for thicker acrylic if needed.
8) Enjoy!
Update: I ended up redoing the switch mechanism. I instead used a bolt and a spring. The bolt makes a contact with the back of the battery and is connected to the wire running to the LED's. It's a cool mod and doesn't require any special parts. It may be a little less reliable, but is much less likely to short.
Feel free to get creative on how to hook up the wiring!

#include 
int oneway;                      // counter for steps
int onerev = 6400;               // number of steps each direction (edit this

int milsec = 250;                // 1 sec = 1000 ms   
                                 // delay between steps and speed of the motor

                                 //   higher number = slower)

int dirPin = 8;                  // output pin for stepper motor direction
int stepPin = 9;                 // output pin for the pin used to step the motor
void setup() {                
  pinMode(dirPin, OUTPUT);       // Assign output mode to pin for direction
  pinMode(stepPin, OUTPUT);      // Assign output mode to pin for setp
  digitalWrite(dirPin, LOW);     // Initialize dir pin 
  digitalWrite(stepPin, LOW);    // Initialize step pin
  oneway = 1;
}
void loop() {
  if (oneway < onerev + 1)            // Still in first revolution?
    {
      digitalWrite(dirPin, LOW);      // Keep direction pin low
    }
  else
    {
      digitalWrite(dirPin, HIGH);    // If not in first revolution change 
                                     //   direction pin to High
    }
  digitalWrite(stepPin, HIGH);       // Step motor

What's that flying beneath the Christmas tree? Why a missile toe of course! Tis the season.

This is designed to fly on an Estes A10-3 - I've not test flown it but it should have the needed kick.

Besides the obvious motors, you will need about 2" of 13mm tube (BT-5), a parachute or a streamer and a short length of 1/8" launch lug.

For now the instructions are
1) Know something about model rocketry
2) Glue the motor block into the end of the BT-5 - you want the motor to be able to stick out about 1/2" or so.
3) Glue the BT-5 into the opening for it on the rocket,
4) Push the 1/8th launch lug into the square mount, there shouldn't be a need to glue it
5) Add a recovery system (chute / streamer / shock cord) and attach it to the motor block and the small hole inside the nose cap.
6) If needed add weight to the nose cone so that the rocket balances about 1" above the fins
7) Fly it, and god speed to the missile toe!

The roof does not need any supports, I tweaked the XY support clearance in Cura3 until only the center ring and the arches had support.

I would not recommend PLA, but I printed all the early tests in PETG and then used them while printing the next revisions, and they held up well as long they had no contact to the hot end. The version released here has good clearances.

The final print pictured here was done in "natural" eSun ePC filament to allow for more clarity under the shroud (to see the nozzle for issues) and also as it is very heat tolerant. It printed much better than the PETG also. Just make sure to allow for 0.8% shrinkage in ePC.

I also set Cura3 for -0.05mm "Horizontal Offset" to correct for encroachment of small openings like the screw holes.

Floor of duct is only 0.6mm thick so be careful removing from printer bed. However, I had no issues with the several test prints I made.

Update: I apparently never uploaded the stl file for the rear corners. Well, now I have. Enjoy! Large ABS 3D prints tend to delaminate during printing if you don't keep them warm while printing. This "thing" is a group of 3D printable parts to make a thermally insulating box from 1" PIR foam to contain your printer. I designed printed pieces to hold the foam boards because I frequently take my printer to demonstrations and I wanted to be able take the box apart and put it back together.
If you don't need to move your printer, just use duct tape to hold the foam pieces together and don't bother printing parts to do it.

Measure your printer and calculate the sizes of the foam pieces you'll need to build the box to enclose it. Cut the pieces in the configuration shown or the printed parts may not work. I used 1" PIR foam with foil on both sides because it is fire retardant, but you could probably get away with polystyrene foam.
You'll need four of the rear corners, two of the front corners, and two of the hinge assemblies. Print as many of the clips as you think you'll need for your box size.
The front and rear corner pieces and the hinges are printed in two parts then superglued together in order to avoid using support material during printing. Print with a 3-5mm brim to prevent corners lifting off the print bed (see the photo of the rear corner).
It's a good idea to tape the edges of the foam pieces to prevent damaging them. 2" packing tape or duct tape works fine. You may want to put some pieces of masonite or wood under your printer's feet, depending on how heavy it is, to prevent them from sinking into the foam.
The hinges are designed so that 6-32 screws will screw tightly into the door hinge pieces and fit loosely in the box hinge piece.
It's also a good idea to move the printer's electronics outside the box- heat and electronics are not a good combination.
1) Cut notches in the foam then put the clips, corners, and hinge on the bottom piece of foam,
2) set your printer on it,
3) add suitably notched back and side pieces of foam,
4) put the clips, corners, and hinge on the suitably notched top piece
5) put the top on the box and press it into place
6) put the door on the hinge
7) cut notches/holes as needed for filament, cables, and windows.
You don't really need to seal the box air tight, so don't worry about small gaps at corners and edges. If you're really paranoid about it you can make "weather strips" using packing tape at the edges of the foam boards.
Update: I measured the temperature inside the box using a thermocouple and found that I had to leave the door open a little to keep the temperature from rising above 42C. My electronics are still inside the box and that was as hot as I wanted to let it get without some provision for cooling the electronics.
The last photo shows a 3 Face Cup (blue) I printed inside the box using ABS. It took about 15 hours to print and exhibits no delamination.

description.text: This is a model of a prokaryotic cell which can serve as a study aid for students in Biology and Microbiology courses. The idea for the model came from the textbook: Microbiology: An Introduction By Gerard J. Tortora, Berdell R. Funke, and Christine L. Case (Pearson).

The model can be printed in a single color and painted. You can instruct students to paint the models as an assignment, or paint them to set up for the assignment. I uses Testors Enamel paints and allow ample time for drying. Or, if using a multicolor printer, you can use the *.amf file as a color refference.

Print the Prokaryotic cell file with the holes if you wish to glue in pipe cleaners for flexible fimbriae and flagella.
Using the referenced Microbiology textbook as a guide, a generic prokaryotic cell was drawn in Autodesk 123D Design.

Overview: The Prokaryotic Cell In the study of biology and microbiology, students learn that all living cells can be classified into two groups: prokaryotic cells and eukaryotic cells. This classification is based on both structural and functional characteristics. The term prokaryote is deriverd from the Greek words meaning "prenucleus" because one of the key factors that distinguishes the prokaryotes is the lack of a nucleus. Other distinguishing features of prokaryotic cells include:
  • They are smaller than eukaryotic cells
  • They generally do not have membrane bound organelles
  • They usually divide by binary fission
  • Their DNA is not associated with histones
  • Their cell walls contain peptidoglycan (a complex polysaccharide)

Flash Card Learning With repetition and a hands-on experience, students will be engaged and learn the prokaryotic cell anatomy faster. In this exercise, a group of two students will cut out the flash cards. One student will hold up a card, while the other student points (using a pointer/straw, or pencil) to where the component is located. Students can take turns and award points for correct answers. Answers can be checked using the attached key. Once it is clear that both students know the names of each component of the cell, have the students write the definition or function of each cellular component on the back of each flash card. Have the students read those definitions/function to their partner and let the partner determine the name of the cell component and have them point to the location on the model.

Flash Card Activity For the flash card activity, Students will need:
  • Flash card handout
  • Scissors
  • At least one prokaryotic cell model per student
• Cell anatomy
45 min

Model Printing Instructions To print this model using the Makerbot Replicator (5th gen.), use the following settings:
Raft: yes
Support: no
Layer height: 0.1 mm
Infill: 20%
*Print setting may need to be adjusted based on your specific printer and print material. If using a multicolor printer, you can use the *.amf file to print in color. Otherwise, the model can be printed in a single color and painted. You can instruct students to paint the models as an assignment, or paint them to set up for the assignment. I uses Testors Enamel paints and allow ample time for drying. Print the Prokaryotic cell file with the holes if you wish to glue in pipe cleaners for flexible fimbriae and flagella.
Further reading: Tortora, Gerard J., et al. “Chapter 4: Functional Anatomy of Prokaryotic and Eukaryotic Cells.” Microbiology: an Introduction, Pearson, 2016.

This a ready to print 3D Model of a Lion . If you love pets you can 3D print it and place it in your office or home. I created this model using SelfCAD software. SelfCAD is a browser-based 3D modeling software that allows one to model, sculpt and print all under one program. Has advanced but easy to use tools that allows one to model advanced models. With SelfCAD you have a guarantee of more than 25, 000 ready to print models and you can upload your models to the cloud for the whole world to see.
SelfCAD is free for students and teachers and for the general users they have a trial period of one month and later pay only $4.99/

Check more details about SelfCAD here: https://www.selfcad.com

Printer Brand:

Printer:

Overview of SelfCAD software To design the above model you must have SelfCAD account. Visit https://www.selfcad.com to sign up for a 30 day free account and thereafter pay $4.99/m. But if you are a student or teacher SelfCAD is free for you. Contact them at [email protected] and they will set the account for you.
Once you have registered simply launch the software and you will be set.

Start Modeling Launch SelfCAD editor and select Image Generator in create section of the top panel as shown in the picture above.
Select an Image you would like to convert to a 3D model by clicking Select an image button. Modifying the Model Amount slider allows you to either engrave or emboss by a certain value. For this type of image the Amount needs to be close to 20 so that it's easy to cut it out later.
I keep Blur setting to a minimum to keep all the details but if you by any reason want to make the shape smoother, feel free to make Blur > 1.
In this example I will not be using Back Carveture because I want the back of the shape to be flat. Take a look at the shapes above to see what difference and Back carveture and Symmetry make. Finalizing the Shape Click finalize button after you are done with the settings. It may take a few seconds to finalize.
Now position the shape in the center of the scene. Enter Position mode either in the basic transformations section in the top panel or from the scene and set x, y, z values to 0. This will make it easier to cut out the shape in the next step.
To cut out the shape we will use Boolean difference. So we need to add a rectangle that is larger than the image generated shape and position it on the edge of the image.
Click and drag a cube from the Basic shapes panel. Use Move and Scale tools to achieve what is shown on the image above.
Select both shapes (the rectangle and image generated shape). Cutting Out the Shape and Making It Printable Click on Boolean icon in the Tools section of the top panel. Select Difference.
Select the rectangle in the Select objects to subtract drop down. Click Apply.
And the model is ready! Now it's not yet printable, but no worries, that's what Magic fix is for.
Select Magix fix tool in the Tools section and click Apply. If you want to see what it does, turn on the wireframe mode in the Scene panel.

Materials and Tools Needed SelfCAD software - Go to www.selfcad.com and create a Free Trial Account (free for 30 days and $4.99 after the free trial expires). Then launch SelfCAD editor (the programs runs in your browser, no installations required).
Select an image - Choose an image you would like to turn into a 3D shape.
Find a 3D printer - If you do not own a printer, use one of many online 3D printing services and have the print sent to you
Choose a printing material - Learn all you need to know about 3D printing materials on our Blog.

• Print this piece in PLA or any material that does not rapidly dissolve in acetone.

  • Place the stand in the coffee can

  • Place an ABS part on top of the stand

  • Close the top and wait a few hours, depending on the desired texture.

description.text:
This is an attempt at a parametric Convergent-Divergent Nozzle, also called a De Laval nozzle. There are two types available: a simpler nozzle with a conic nozzle extension; and a more complex and efficient nozzle with a parabolic bell extension. I modeled the conic first, and built upon that foundation to model the parabolic bell by using a bezier curve. It is close, and is a very good approximation, but could use a bit of help from someone more mathematically inclined.
Please contribute at:
https://github.com/Buback/ParametricDeLavalModel Updated 3/24/2014: added correct combustion chamber and throat supports. the supports should make the printed piece stronger, but the slicing is more complex and error prone.
updated again 3/25/2014: thanks to Bill Waters for help finding p1. Bell is now modeled correctly. I've also been messing around with an intake, and flipped the whole engine upside down for printing the combustion chamber. the intake will really only work with steam or pressurized gas, for playing with.
4/18/2014: the newest version doesn't have the intake, but the geometry of the bell is now based on the expansion ratio instead of hard dimensions. you enter in the throat radius and the expansion ratio(Exit area/throat area) and it will calculate the proper exit radius. there is still the variables there to enter in fixed radii, and there's an echo to tell you the expansion ratio if you need a certain exit radius.

the conic nozzle has three main parameters:
combustion chamber radius
throat radius
Exit nozzle radius there are also two angles:
the divergent nozzle cone angle
the convergent nozzle cone angle The bell nozzle is much more complex, but is mainly driven by the same ones. I've tried to throughly comment the file, but if you can't find a variable, ask me.

comments.text: I know that this is a late post (many months late) but thought that it would be useful for other readers.  A convergent/divergent nozzle like this will certainly produce supersonic flow ----- IF (and only if) the pressure differential between in and out are high enough.  Primarily it is the inflow pressure.  I do not readily have the formula, but once you get enough pressure to drive sonic flow (i.e. a shockwave) in the throat, the outflow will be supersonic.  Even simple conical shapes do this well.  Maybe not efficiently, but supersonic nonetheless.  I do not know the minimum pressure/throat numbers to generate this shockwave.....I  am a low-end rocket scientist (in other words, I am a mad scientist:) ).

I recently saw this Instructable http://www.instructables.com/id/Disposable-flatware-clock/ by Samuel Bernier and I loved the look of it so I had to go ahead and do it myself....3D printed version (not the plasticware....but i could :D) Materials:
clock
plasticware (approx 15mm wide on the handle side)
3d printer
glue Steps:
-Get a clock from the closest dollar store and take it apart
-Fit the actual clock in the 3d printed model
-The plasticware goes in the railings (they were designed 30 degrees apart from each other so you'll get a clock as straight as it can be
-Paint it in whatever color scheme you want
-Enjoy your new awesome clock I still need to laser cutter my plasticware but I'll post the final result pictures over the weekend Comments, questions and suggestions are very much appreciated! 99% of the credit goes to Samuel :) P.S: you can find the 3d model here:

description.text:
Just a page where I am going to upload all my mods for Ferjerez's "Micro-Sketch".

Better Base: I never got the base to print with Simplify3D, so I combined a few pieces into one printable base that will work with Simplify3D.

Draw Area Gear: My daughter is very young and had trouble keeping the paper in place...so this gives you an area to lock a piece of paper into.

Short Y Axis Pen Holder combined: Trimmed length so it's just long enough if you use the "Draw Area Gear" and it also includes a much easier to print pen holder combined into one piece. In the future I will design a printable closure for it...right now I just use small nut/bolts.

**I'll upload quite a few other pieces I'm working on still such as:

A base mod with spots for magnets so you can stick on the fridge and write notes to the family.

Shorter x,y lengths for smaller build areas

1 piece knob/gears for easier printing

etc, etc

***All design credit goes to Ferjerez, as I've just used calipers and based everything off his original design.

description.text:
These are some pieces that allow you to convert the standard extruder setup into a bowden setup.
This is a mod for 3mm filament. UPDATE :
Added dual-hotend versions so you can start experimenting with multi-color printing !

Minimal instructions if you have a stock printrbot
  • print a extruder-to-bodwen and a bowden-to-hotend
  • Install the Pneufit adapters on your bowden cable and screw it onto the 2 printed pieces
  • install this on your printer
    • Extended instructions - if you're feeling adventurous

  • If you want to mount your extruder to the x-idler, print the gregs_to_bowden-X-idler.stl instead of the regular one. It can hold a horizontal bearing and fits over your z-axis ( on the X-idler side )

  • If you have a reprapfab hotend, use the bowden-to-hotend-reprapfab.stl file
    • Experimental instructions - to go where no one has gone before.
  • If you want to experiment with 2-color extrusion, you can also pick a dual-hotend bowden-to-hotend version ( I rendered a regular one for a UBIS hotend, and a reprapfab version , with 20mm distance between the extruder tips ). This was never tested, and would most likely require modifications in the electronics and software to accomodate an extra extruder on a printrbot.
    But I'd love to see somebody take this challenge !
    • Notes: I used 50cm of PTFE tubing, 3.18inner/6outer diameter (10cm)
    http://reprapworld.com/?products_details&products_id=166 And 2x Pneufit straight adaptor,1/8inx6mm
    http://reprapworld.com/?products_details&products_id=168 And a UBIS hot-end ( stock Printrbot extruder ) The bowden-to-hotend is just a modified version of the Greg's Wade reloaded extruder body, so you can create hotend mounts for any supported hotends ( malcolm, groovemount, arcol, mendel_parts_v6, jhead, reprapfaborg and others )
    If you want to modify the bowden-to-hotend, you'll need the configuration.scad and jonaskuehling-default.scad include files from Greg's Wade Reloaded ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18379 )

description.text: trying to emulate glassblowing in wings 3d. probably my favorite attempt at it.

I was wanting to fit a DRO onto my lathe tailstock.
Found some designs within thingverse but didn't exactly fit the needs so designed this very basic version.
The mini lathe is a 7x14, a very common chinese type of lathe, this one supplied by amadeal (UK).
The tailstock quill is 26mm diameter.
This was designed to use a 6"/150mm digital caliper, these are very popular and can be obtained from many sources, the general design/dimensions are very similar between manufacturers.
The caliper will require to be modified in order to fit onto the bracket and fit within the space constraints of the tailstock. A grinder could be used to cut of the unnecessary parts.
The bracket for holding the caliper onto the tailstock is merely glued onto the tailstock, after providing a "key" for the adhesive to stick to the painted surface of the tailstock, there is no need to sand down to the metal provided the painted surface is sound condition.
The second part of the bracket is clamped onto the tailstock quill and also onto the modified caliper. A 4mm cap screw and nut is used to secure the bracket onto the quill. Three screws (4mm) are used to secure the modified caliper onto the bracket.
This design allows the disconnection of the caliper and removal of the quill bracket if this is ever required.
On my tailstock, in order to detach the drill chuck, the quill had to be retracted fully into the tailstock body, a modification of the drill chuck may be required to enable earlier disengagement. The rotating centre had no such problem. The tailstock also required a redesigned locking lever (slightly taller), but that shouldn't be a problem...you have a lathe....right?
Version 2 of the quill bracket has more material for the clamping screws and a little more "body" at the clamping screw side as version 1 showed signs of splitting.
Have found the 26mm hole a bit tight on the quill, not unusable, just tight. Version 2 has this expanded to 26.4mm. (this has not been printed to see if its acceptable as yet).
Sketchup files are included in case you need to make minor modifications to suit your application.

title: The stopnut : a tool to help you screwing M3

description.text:
Hi friends,

Don't know for you, but when I need to use my M3 screws, the nut is always at the wrong place : at the bottom of an inaccessible place. Not easy to access and even harder more to maintain at its place.

So I created this wonderful gadget : the stopnut!

It is a simple cube with the place for an M3 nut at the bottom. The cube is pierced. It let the screw pass through to let you use any length of screw. So, you can position the nut at it's ideal place and maintain it during the screwing. I have chosen a square section and not a cylinder because it's easier to catch it firmly and if it turns that is immediately visible.

To complete it I have added a normal wrench. I have added too a support for finger for some special positions where you need to maintain the nut and the piece together.

In brief, this little stopnut, try to be as universal as possible.. for it's aim :). However If you have any suggestion let me a comment or a message.

Hope you'll like it. Feel free to comment or post pictures if you print it.
